{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_fifteen_ver01/data/sn85058397/paper/1910102701/0945.xml":{"full_text":"on\nrr\nI\nt\nJ\nr 1\nI J\nII j 4 THE EVENING STANDARD OGDEN UTAH THURSDAY OCTOBER 27 1910 C\nW11f fEuruil1g ttt1tbar\nPublished Daily Except Sundays by Wm Glasmann\nAFearless Independent Newspaper It\nHas No Friends to Reward and No Enemies\nI\nto Punish\nHEAR ALL SIDES\nWhile This Paper Has Strong Republican Predilections I\ni it Is Not a Party Organ and Its News Columns are Fair and\n1 lust to All Parties and Creeds\nNEW ROAD OUT OF OGDEN\nr The Los Angeles Times speaks of the lately connected aqueduct\nline from Los Angeles north through Owens Valley as a connecting\ni link with the roads of Utah which is destined to win its place among\nthe great transcontinental routes\nWhen the entire road is standard gauged overland trains for\nLos Angeles will proceed from Ogden west over the Southern Pa\ncific to Hazen and thence south direct to Southern California over\none of the most scenic and inviting roads in the West As compared\nwith the San Pedro though a little longer it will be a more desir\nable route especially in summer when the heat on the Clark road in\nsouthern Nevada is almost unbearable\nWILL MAINTAIN THIS VIADUCT\nThe Oregon Short Line is proceeding with the construction of\nthe viaduct over the railroad yards in Pocatello The railroad we\nare informed is doing the work at its own expense and will main\ntain the structure after completion\nThat is what the railroad should have done in Ogden but\nthrough the liberality of our city guardians failed to do when the\nJ viaduct was constructed on Twentyfourth street\nti With all our kowtowing and salaaming we do not know that\nf we are in higher favor or are ina position to get more from the\n10 railroads than other communities that exact straight business\ndealing when negotiations with those great corporations\nJUDGE MAGINNIS DEATH\nJ\nl Judge Maginnis who died last Wednesday morning after an\nillness of many months was a man who made friends He had\nf an entire community of wellwishers and his death came as a shock\nOJ although he was known to be seriously ill\ni He was courageous to the last The day before he died he\nt attended court in Salt Lake in defense of a client He must have\nrealized that the end was near but he possessed a remarkable will\ni power which defied even Death\nOne of the judges before whom he practiced said that as a law\nyer he was most capable and his appointment by Grover Cleveland\nas chief justice of Wyoming prior to his coming to Ogen supports\nthat statement\nOgden and Utah has lost a citizen of worth and one little\ni\nfamily is deprived of a good husband and father in the death of\nI Judge W L Maginnis\nI I HOW UTAH WILL SUFFER\ni\nI\nI\nAfter reading our editorial of last evening on Utah a Gentile\nn whose leanings have been toward those who are keeping up a cam\npaign of defamation against the people of Utah by circulating un\n1 favorable criticism in Eastern publications said he had seen a new\nI light and from now on will labor to discourage any movement which\nI has for its object the discrediting of Utah among the American peo\nple as a whole\nI HI have reached the conclusion we can solve our own problems\nwithout appealing to others II he said Ie as our differences are those\nj of a family and not for the scandal mongers on the outside\nI I i i Those who seek to keep this Mormon issue an endless source of\nII 1 1 u\nII 1\nI i Oysters Served e Shore\nCannot Surpass These\nI\nIi o\ni r\n1\n1 Oysters served you at the shorefresh from I\nI the oyster bedscould not satisfy you more than\nE genuine Sealshipt Oysters with the delicious tang\nI of the sea They come straight from the seashore\nI I to us under ice and under seal all the way\nI I I I Scalshipl Oysters are sold only by registered agents of the\nj Sealshipt Oyster System We are bonafide agents I\nI r I You can identify us by the blue and\nI I I white Sealshipticase the handsome porce I\nl lain store refrigerator which conserves r\nI r I the natural freshness and flavor of the 1\ni I oyster 1\nl I\ni I I I i Look for the trademark on the Seal f\nI shipticasc See the name and address of\nthe Sealshipt Oyster System near the I\nbottom I\nI\nI Then you are sure of the worlds best\noystersas fresh and delicious as the hour I\nI I they came from the oceanthe moment WI1 rlpr rill in wbi th I\nuo hind you Scahhipl\nl they were removed from the shell hUlgJ\nI\nr\ni L Sealshipt Oyst rs\nThe Cream of the Oyster Beds\nI Genuine Sealshipt Oysters embrace the cream\nof Uie worlds best oysters Blue Points Narra\nI gansctts Grcenports Chesaixiakcs Gulfstiny\noysters you want with every iiutnlivc clement\nt eavcd every natural flavor and savor conserved\ni\nI I I F Yon can depend absolutely on the purity of\nI Eq ljI b Alshipt Oysters The waters where these\nj f ttip oysters arc grown are not only supervised by\n4N w li r State and federal Government but arc analyzed\n11 oy the Ledcrlc Laboratones the famous food\n1 experts\nII\nEtsuslrrOisu t Sealshipt Oysters arc all solid oyster meat\nno water no waste hence their vast economy\nI 1htoBIIIIIrod Wblle The price of Scalshipt Oysters is the sUmcLird of\ni StoroFhluro frotntthicbwoujl value If you pay less you get less Aak for Free\nSubhipt Ojilen fool of recipes for delicious oyster dishes\nWe Are Registered Sealshipt Agents\nI I H L GRIFFIN COMPANY\nJobbing Distributors\nPHIL GRILL\nSUCCESS\nMEAT MARKET\nj BALLARD S EBELING WASHINGTON MARKET\nLONDON MEAT MARKET A M Miller Prop\nF Wright Prop\nI\nc\nt\ndiscord will continue to do as some arc now doing They will dis\ngust the stranger and wall in Utah with prejudice until the ostracism\nis complete they will keep out the broadening influence of immi\ngration and allow the shriveling effect of seclusiyeness to continue\nto work against progress\nREVIEW OF BUSINESS\nThe most important single element of improvement of busi\nness says Henry Clews is the positive assurance of a bumper corn\ncrop As a result of the big corn yield our Western farmers and\nmerchants have each put on a spirit of renewed confidence so that\nalready the business outlook throughout the great corn belt is show\ning real improvement Pessimism never so deep in the West as in\nthe East is now rapidly disappearing for the farmers will be able\nto meet their obligations and land speculation has received a whole\nsome quietus through the timely efforts exerted by interior bankers\nIncoming advices from the West are all of a much more favorable na\nture than a few weeks ago\nThe New York banker in reviewing the business outlook and\ncommenting on influences at work to aid or retard industry says\nAmong the favorable political indications are the moderating\nof public hostility to corporations the belief that the Supremo\nCourt will not destroy property rights and the expectation that\nthe railroads will secure reasonable treatment in their request for\nadvanced rates All of these considerations have combined to stim\nulate a revival of confidence in security markets A somewhat bet\nter demand for bonds has also recently developed This is partly\nan indication of increased confidence is partlydue to accumula\ntion of funds seeking investment and partly to a realization of the\nfact that bonds are really not endangered by any probable action\nwhich the Interstate Commerce Commission may take on the rate\nsituation President McCreas thoroughly sound and temperate ar\ngument in favor of better rates created a strong impression i not only\nin investment circles but also among shippers who are fighting all\nadvances among political leaders at Washington and among the\npetty politicians who have been ignorantly assuming that clubbing\nthe railroads was good for votemaking Everything now indicates\nthat the railroad problem will be solved along lines of recognized\nrights of both railroads and shippers and that justice will be dealt\nout as evenly as possible to each and every interest\nOur foreign trade is showing a very remarkable and satis\nfactory change towards more normal conditions In September our I\nexports wore valued at nearly 169000000 This was nearly 15000\n000 in excess of last year and was probably the heaviest September\non record The increase was partly due to heavy cotton shipments\nImports during the same month amounted to only 117000000 a\ndecrease of nearly 4000000 compared with last year Tho net\nresult for the month was an excess of exports of 51000000 com\npared with 330000000 in 1909 and nearly 41000000 in 1908\nThis change in the tendency of our foreign trade is wholesome and\nsignificant\nThe financial outlook is quite favorable as there is evidence of\nless stringency All anxiety about the local money market has now\ndisappeared I says Financier Clews Temporary stringency may\noccur between now and the first of the year and the importance of\nthe advance in the Bank of England rate should not be overlooked\nIt is a warning that must be heeded If all reports are true con\nsiderable amounts of American finance bills have been placed abroad\nand should Europe liquidate American stocks with any freedom we\nmight find ourselves shortly exporting gold at a season when imports\nare customary On the other hand funds withdrawn for crop mov\ning purposes will soon begin to return from the West and with\nlower prices for commodities and the lessened activity of business\nthere should be no scarcity of loanable funds The excess of loans\nover deposits in some sections of the country is an indication of un\nsatisfactory conditions which in time will probably right themselves\nThe fear of a local crisis which hung over this market all summer\nhas now quietly disappeared General business continues quiet ana\nit will be some weeks if not several months before the full effects\nof a good harvest display themselves especially as the process of\nreadjustment to new conditions is not entirely completed After the\nelections it would not be surprising if a moderate resumption of\nactivity was to occur The improvement in the security market will\nundoubtedly act as a stimulant\nBETWEEN PROPOSAL AND PERFORMANCE\nThis would be a grand world to live in if theory and practice could\nonly be got to jibo From time to time someone comes forward wit\na bold claim that he can take lead or copper and turn it into gold\nThe public always puts faith in these claims for the idea is attractive\nbut the fact remains that these goldmakers invariably die poor\nDr F W Lange of Scranton is the latest man to assert his dis\ncovery of the philosophers stonebut his property has recently been\nseized by his creditors his brother who loaned him large sums of\nembezzled funds has absconded and in spite of the recipe for making\ngold the family is bankrupt\nWhen you see a problem that has defied the ability of the ages\nto solve you might as well be modest about proclaiming a solution\nof it All problems will be solved in time but only in their logical\ncourse We cant jump from simple addition tocalculus we must\nwork our way up to the higher science through a long chain of related\nprocesses\nMany big problems of our social and political life have such a\nsimple look that we jiimp to the conclusion that they arc easy They\nare not easy else they would have been solved long before this There\nare difficulties involved in them which we cannot see until we get\nwound up in them\nIt looks simple to prohibit the liquor traffic in a state yeb in\npractice it is a most difficult matterso difficult that actual prohibi\ntion is unknown We must educate public sentiment up to a higher\nplane of moral understanding before it can be a thorough success\nThe Socialists after getting control of the government of Milwau\nkee are impatient with Mayor Seidel because many of the reforms\nwhich they thought would come at once must for one reason or an\nother be delayed or given up\nFOR HIGHER FREIGHT RATES\nEminent railroad men from all parts of the country have been\nexplaining to the interstate commerce commission at Washington why\nthe railroads should be allowed to increase freight rates This is a\nvital question for the industries and prosperity of the country are in\nlarge measure involved in the railroad problem\nPresident McCroa of the Pennsylvania testified that during the\npast 10 years the wages of railway workers had been increased 33 per\ncent During that period his road had spent 262000000 in improve\nments such as better terminals heavier equipment etc It was to the\ninterest of the people of this country said he that railroad service\nshould be ample and efficient but it would be impossible to find cap\nital to carry on improvements unless fair profits wore assured\nI\nSome of the biggest shippers in the country have joined the rail\nroads and the railway labor unions in urging increases in freight\nrates They say that in order that trade shall thrive there must be\nmore and better means of transportation and that if railway better\nments are now stopped it will be a heavy blow to business of all\nkinds It is better they argue to pay a little more freight than to\nsuffer a paralysis of trde is a result of squeezing the railroads\nDEATHS AND r\nL FUNERALS I\nVIOLA DYKEMAN\nTho funernl cervices of Viola May\nthe five year old daughter of Mr and\nMrs C A DyUemnn were held yes\nterday from LJnilanlst Sons liner\ned chapel at 230 oclock Rev H\nD Zimmerman officiated and Mrs\nZimmerman rendered tho musical\nnumbers There was a large attend\nance at tho senicos Interment took\nplace In the Ogden city cemetery\n10 THE PUBLIC\nTho Denver Ro Grande is the\nofficial line for tho High school foot\nball excursion to Salt Lake October\n20th Advertisements to the contrary\nby other railroads are unllUthorized\nRemember tho official train leaves\nat 900 a in October 29th over tho\nDenver St Rio Grande Round trip\nFaro 1 00 Special train returning at\n730 p m\nJOHN M MILLS\nSupU Schools\n1 0 CROSS\nPrincipal Ogden High School\nSickness and Disease\nI\nCaused by Eating Un\nclean Meats\nPROTECTIVE MEASURES\nAVAILABLE\nIn the Morning Examiner of Juno\n26th the following description Is giv\nen of one of tho local slaughter\nhouses by An Old Subscilbcr\nHere IB a place where the meats\nwe cut aro prepared The blood from\ntho animals slaughtered runs through\ntho cracks of tho floor The entrails\nare thrown right outside the door\nIn under tLc iloor and outside tho\ndoor In all of thin corrupted mat\nter the maggots thrive by the mil\nlions The moats that are put on\ntho blocks the next day In Ogdon\nhang In the center of these disease\nbreeding aurroundlngs the air so foul\nthat It compels neighbors for miles\naround to complain\nTo complete the scene wo have\nswarms of flies alighting on this cor\nruption and carrying this filth onto\nthe meats and yet wo wonder whero\nall our sickness and disease como\nfrom when such meats actually are\nsold at some of what we call our best\nmeat markets In the city\nCompare ahoyo with tho following\nextracts from U S Regulation No\n1C Governing U S Inspected pack\nIng plants\nSection 3 Official establishments\nshall be suitably lighted and ventilat\ned and maintained In a sanitary con\ndition and shall be provided with\nefficient drainage having properly\ntrapped or other approved sewer con\nnections\nSection 4 Ceilings walls pillars\npartitions etc shall be kept In a\nsanitary condition and when neces\nsary they shall bo Washed scraped\npainted or otherwise treated as re\nquired\nSection 5 All truck trays and oth\ner receptacles all chutes platforms\nracks tables etc and all knives\nsaws cleavers and other tools and\nall utensils machinery and vehicles\nused in moving handling cuttln\nchopping mixing canning or other\nprocesses hall be thoroughly cleaned\nbefore using\nSection 7 Persons affected with\ntuberculosis or any other communi\ncable disease shall not be employed\nIn any of the departments of estab\nlishments\nSection 9 The rooms or compart\nments In which meat or meat food\nproducts arc prepared cured stored\npacked shai be kept free from flies\nand other vermin by screening or\nother methods\nSection 10 All yards fences pens\nchutes alloys etc belonging to tho\npremises ol such establishments\nwhether they are used or not shall\nbe maintained In a sanltnry condi\ntion\nSection 11 Butchers who dress or\nhandle diseased carcasses or parts\nshall cleanse their hands of all grease\nand then Immerse them In a prescribed\ndisinfectant and rinse them In clear\nwater before dressing or handling\nhealthy carcasses\nThere Is only ono Government In\nspected plant In operation In Utah\nThis Is tho plant of the Ogden Pack\nIng Provision Co with O lIen and\nSalt Lako City as Its main dlstrlbut\nlag points Hero the government\nhas stationed ono Veterinary sur\ngeon and two meat inspectors to see\nthat all tho above regulations are\nCompiled with besides a host of\nothers\nYou guard In many ways against\ndisease but If you use uninspected\nmeats you allow disease to enter\nyour home\nTo use Inspected meats will reduce\nyour doctor bills eliminate sickness\nand suffering and prolong the lives\nof yourself and family\nGovernment inspected moats aro\nhandled exclusively at the neat mar\nkets listed below Is your market\nlisted\nSawyer Bros Chicago Market Bal\nlard C Belnap California Market\nBlel C Son Ogden Moat Co Mould\ning Moat S Grocery Co Wright Meat\nit Grocery Co and Scager Meat\nGrocery Co\nBANKRUPTCY\nIN TUB DISTRICT COURT OF THE\nUnited States for the district of\nUtah Before A B Patton referee\nIn the matter of Don IT Wbolsoy\nbankrupt In bankruptcy No LI01\nTo the creditors of Don II Woolaey\nof Ogden City in the county of Weber\nand the district aforesaid a bankrupt\nNotice Is hereby given that on the\n2lst day of October A D 1010 the\nsaid Don IT Vooleey was duly adju\ndicated a bankrupt and that the first\nmeeting of his creditors will be bold\nat my office room 11 Federal building\nOgden City Weber county Utah on\nthe 7th day of November A nI 1010\nat 1030 oclock In the forenoon at\nwhich time the creditors may meN\nprove their claims appoint trustee\nexamine the bankrupt and transact\nsuch other business as may properly\ncome beforo said meeting\nA B PATTON\nReferee\nOgden Utah October 27 1910\nBAMBERGER EXCURSION\nThe Bambcrgor line will run a I\nmammoth excursion business Satur\nday Oct 29th from Ogden to Salt\nOGDEN t\nONE NIGHT ONLY\nFriday fl October 28 I\nJOHN CORT presents\nIAX FaN l\nIn his greatest success f\nThe Delightful Comedy Drama by Edith Ellis\nMARY JANES PA\nSAME GREAT COMPANY SAME GREAT PRODUCTION\nAs seen here last season\nTHE PLAY THAT ALL AMERICA WANTS TO SEE\nIT MEANS HAPPINESS\nSEATS NOW SELLING\nPayees ogQ 8100 75c 50c 25c\nNext AHrac ion Mark Swain Co in\n66 Madams Divorce or 6G Bivorcons\nStillIrndlay October 30th\nIA\nv f\nThe R oycz oft Store i\n358 25th Street\nJddenP s Most Popular\n1ens Store\ns H BROWN co\nTUrfW i DJfalillUIhl 1ii Good Aecorn\nOften in winter you dare not Fj\nA note\nopen a window even though the J\nroom be warm because the cold\ni rt fr air makes a draught that is dan\n1Y g rous With a Perfection Oil\nHeater there need be no danger\nA from draughts\nOpen the lower part of the s\nwindow a little put the Perfection 1\nOil Heater in front of it and the\ncold draught will be turned into a i\nr pleasant healthful current of fresh ff\nt t air The\n9 r 1\nf\nAnaCt Eat15GJ\nAbsolutely smokeless and odorless\ngives just as much heat as you desire It is safe odorless and\nsmokeless Has an automaticlocking name spreader\nwhich prevents the wick from being turned high enough to\nsmoke and is easy to remove to clean and drop back Burner\nbody or gallery cannot become wedged because of a new device\ntherefor it can be easily and quickly unscrewed for rewicking\nAn indicator shows the amount of oil in the font Has a cool\nhandle Fillercnp is put in place like a cork In a bottle and is\na